Ethical Scenarios Name
Broadcasting
Ethics discussion scenarios. Read the Scenario and answer how you would approach the story.
Scenario 1: A student in your school commits suicide. Do you report it? If so, how and when?
What are the considerations in covering such a situation?
I would report this after all details are released with a tribute and to tell everyone that knew the
person to go to the funeral.
Scenario 2: A website (www.ratemyteachers.com, for example) allows students to rate their
teachers and other people can search by school and see ratings results. A teacher at your
school has received a really bad rating. Is this a story you can cover and if so how?
Reporting this story is not important for the public to know, but if that was the case, the
administrators should handle this.
Scenario 3: Special needs students deserve to be covered. Their stories can often provide
insight and inspiration for others. But, there are many special circumstances that present
challenges in tact and approach. Ethically, do you interview students who have difficulty
speaking clearly? Is it possible you could expose them to ridicule by airing their remarks? How
much do you show these kids struggling with everyday tasks? What about written permission to
tape them? The ultimate challenge: How can you be fair to these kids and their families, and get
their stories across while respecting and protecting them?
Learn about each situation and report the story in a professional manner. If the family wants to
be private, use censors or do not do the story at all.
Scenario 4: The schools football team is not having a good season. They have been losing by
large margins. Some of last years starters were not eligible because of their grades, which has
affected this years success. Parents in the Athletic Boosters and the local radio sportscasters
have been very critical of the coaching staff. Your weekly news broadcast to the student body is
live and content decisions are made by the student producers. However, the principal has
instructed that sports stories about the football team should only present a positive angle. What
should the student producer and sports reporters do?
Do not report the story at all.
Scenario 5: A senior athlete, 18 years old, signs a football scholarship with your state
university. A week later, a reporter on your staff happens to see the athletes vehicle being
searched. Drugs are found, including what appears to be a syringe. A few minutes later, the
athlete is called to the principals office. There are two big district playoff games coming up.
During the following week, nothing happens to the athlete in question. He is at school every day,
practices every afternoon, and plays on Friday nightsuffering no apparent consequences for
the drugs. Your reporter wants to look into this. What is your response? What are the issues
involved? Are there parameters the reporter must respect? Is the story worth it?
Do not report this story. If you were to though, put the headline as Principal has back-door deal
with Football Star. If you do not get enough info, do not release the story.
Scenario 6: A student reporter wants to do a story about waitresses who works at Hooters. He
knows that Hooters will not allow him to record inside the restaurant and that even if he could,
the waitress would not give candid answers. Therefore, he comes up with a plan to hide a
wireless mic in his sleeve and have a friend sit at another table with a small camera on his cell
phone to secretly record while he tries to engage the waitress in an interview. What will you tell
him about his plan and the story in general?
Ethically, do not report this story. If you were to, after the recording, ask if the story could be
released.
Scenario 7: The school held a sensitivity awareness day for the whole school and one of the
main themes was name-calling. Some of the words that were discussed were racial slurs and
words that are derogatory to women. A student producer wants to include a story about the
days activities on the show, which is produced for both in-house student body and community
access cable. The producer wants to include some of the actual words that were discussed in
order to fully report the story. Some of the staff members, and even the advisor, feel that this is
a legitimate part of the news and agree that this is one way to excite controversy for a newscast
that is not widely watched. What would you tell this group about how to cover this story?
Do not target anyone with this story and just report it.
Scenario 8: A student is producing a package about shopping/buying habits of teens. He has
shot outside a mall (because the mall will not allow cameras inside). The reporter shows you the
footage of his stand-up, which ends with Lets interview some of the teens headed to the mall
today to do some shopping. Just then, the reporters best friend walks into the frame and the
reporter does, what is meant to look like, a chance to interview with a typical teenage shopper
who just happened to pass by at that time. However, its obvious to you, the teacher, that this
interview was probably planned in advance and staged for the camera. What would you tell your
student?
Just say the average things they like to buy at the mall.
Scenario 9: Your student has a sound bite on tape that is too long to be used in its entirety.
Still, there are really good comments at the beginning and the person gets really heated with
emotion at the end. The student wants to use the beginning and the end and cut out the middle.
What would you tell him to do? Is it ethical not to use the whole sound bite? Is it ethical to edit
and put it all together as one piece, as though that were the way it was spoken? If not, would it
be ok to use the part, insert a reporter VO, and then insert the last part? What ethical concerns
exist here?
Just edit the good parts with the beginning and end, but not too much with the end.
Scenario 10: A student is producing a story about a nature trail that is being built by the forestry
class. His B-roll does not have any natural sound. He was too far away from the little stream
that is in the area to pick up any sound of water trickling over the rocks. No birds were singing
when he shot. In fact, his B-roll is full of comments made by the students who were there
working on the trail. He plans to mute the sounds of talking and he thinks he can add some
sound of water and birds from a sound-effects library and make the mood of his story a lot
better. What do you tell him?
Try getting the student interview at a different time with more sounds. Compare the footage and
choose the best one.
Scenario 11: Your students are preparing for their regular newscast and this particular show
airs on April Fools Day. They want to produce one or more stories and include announcements
that are fictional, but in a news setting and news format. Their motivation is to trick the viewers
in a gotcha manner as a celebration of April Fools Day. Is this ethical? Is this advisable?
This is ethical if you do it the right way. No heavy stories allowed.
